Analysis of Spike Counts as Proxy for Excitability

A common argument regarding neurophysiological activity changes during reorganization following ischemia is that deficits observed during post-stroke motor paresis relate to unbalanced "aggregate excitation" as evidenced by the total counts of unit spiking in layers with presumptive descending projections to the spinal cord. One hypothesis is that this imbalance is caused by the loss of inhibition contralateral to the injury that was previously supplied by the callosal fibers which degrade when cell bodies in the ischemic tissue are lost. In turn, this may cause hyper-excitability of the intact hemisphere, which strengthens inhibition of the injured hemisphere via its own callosal projections.
We did not test this hypothesis explicitly. Rather, we simply wanted to test the data that we collected against existing hypotheses in the field. One can imagine that many confounding covariates would be present in a study designed to test unit dynamics during motor behavior, with respect to a simple comparison of aggregate multi-unit rates between the two hemispheres. Therefore, this script is provided wherein the first part allows the user to manipulate the defined epoch window as well as the alignment behavior, to generate the statistical results as needed and actively compare the resulting output.
% "Run All" button (not shown in html export)

Load Data

clc;
clearvars -except R G
if exist('R','var')==0
R = getfield(load(defaults.files('raw_rates_table_file'),'R'),'R');
end

Ad hoc model generator

This section allows the user of the live-script to generate a statistical model by inserting fixed timing epoch and alignment parameters as desired. If you are reading the html-exported version, or just want to skip to the results part, click here.
In the batch script analyze_raw_rates.m, we used some fixed periods around behavioral alignments, based on the general observation that task-related modulation of unit activity fluctuates on a timescale of a few hundred milliseconds near motor events of interest. In this case, we selected TASK_EPOC = [-450,150] for the task epoch in each of the three alignments, and TASK_EPOC = [-1350,-750] in alignment to Reach only as a "non-behavior" epoch. When modifying the values of TASK_EPOC below, the first value must be lower than the second value. Click Run Section when parameters are configured as desired.
mdl = "Spikes~Group*Area+(1+SupportLimbMovement|ChannelID:Day)+(1+Duration+Extension+Retraction|AnimalID)"; % Wilkinson notation model
For statistics, we will fit a generalized linear mixed-effects model for a Poisson-distributed variable (spike counts in some epoch of interest) using a log link function. We will maximize the model log-likelihood using the Laplace fit method. In addition, any exclusion information is included with the glme variable in the output table G at the end of this script.
The model is defined using Wilkinson Notation, which includes main effects and interaction effects when terms are specified using the * operator. The only fixed terms in the model are:
  • Group: Categorical variable with levels Intact and Ischemia (experimental rats; received vasoconstrictive injections of ET-1 in primary motor area that controls reaching forelimb).
  • Area: Categorical variable with levels RFA (Rostral Forelimb Area; rat area homologous to premotor cortex; contralateral to the forelimb retrieving the pellet) and CFA (Caudal Forelimb Area; rat area homologous to primary motor cortex; ipsilateral to the forelimb retrieving the pellet).
  • Group*Area (interaction)
  • Intercept
The rest of the model includes two groupings of Random effects, which are actually pretty crucial in fitting the model well (the main thing being that each channel should have a random intercept term that has a nested grouping by day). There is also a grouped random effect for animal, which includes Duration of the total reach, the Extension duration, and Retraction duration, since each of these things influence how "close" temporally the behavioral events of interest are relative to one another through the execution of the behavior.
ALIGN = 'Grasp'; % Parameter-1: Event
TASK_EPOC = [-990 ,450]; % Parameter-2: Relative epoch (ms)
% "Run Section" button (not shown in html export)
adhoc_glme = analyze.stat.fit_spike_count_glme(R,ALIGN,'Successful',TASK_EPOC,'Model',mdl);

Note that we are using counts of spikes instead of spikes normalized by duration, so depending on the length of time that is specified in TASK_EPOC, there will be a bias toward more or less spikes.

GLME model export for Test Statistic Endpoints

Values generated here were used in the corresponding Results discussion section of the associated manuscript.

Align = {'Reach';'Grasp';'Grasp';'Support';'Reach'}; % Pellet-retrieval behavioral event alignment
Outcome = {'Successful';'Successful';'Unsuccessful';'Successful';'All'}; % Pellet-retrieval Outcome filter
tStart = [-450; -450; -450; -450; -1350]; % Relative epoch start times (ms)
tStop = [ 150; 150; 150; 150; -750]; % Relative epoch end times (ms)

In both groups, during Reach onset, there is a higher expected number of spikes in Caudal Forelimb Area (CFA) ipsilateral to the forelimb reaching out of the box to retrieve the pellet. This may make sense, since it's possible this activation relates to some sort of postural support taking place using the non-reaching limb.

Model 2: multi-unit spike counts during Grasp onset. The shape of the expected output manifold for the generalized linear mixed-effects model with the same structure as Model 1 changes somewhat as the temporal region-of-interest shifts from Reach to Grasp. In addition to a significant effect of Area (p << 0.001; DF = 29510; tStat = -6.42), there is now a significant interaction effect for Group*Area (p = 0.016; DF = 29510; tStat = 2.42). The model again predicts that in general there is a lower expected value of spikes during this behavioral epoch in RFA by comparison to CFA, but now there is a significant difference in the relative fall-off from CFA-predicted spikes to RFA-predicted spikes in the Ischemia group, which is statistically significant. This is interesting, because it goes against the Interhemispheric Inhibition hypothesis. An alternative is that there is still interhemispheric inhibition, but the reorganization of activity related to the "redistribution of function" necessary of the remaining cells that survive in the hemisphere with the lesion leads them to become more active for some reason around the Grasp.

Model 4: multi-unit spike counts during Support onset. The model for Support onset is similar to the model for Reach (Model 1), and makes sense; we would expect that during movement of the supporting forelimb, M1 in the intact hemisphere contralateral to the supporting forelimb would be more active than premotor cortex in the hemisphere ipsilateral to it. When we align specifically to a supporting forelimb movement, coherence to that behavioral event is stronger than to the other elements of behavior that are presumably co-occurring. Therefore, we expect this activity to "outweight" any coherent averaging of activity related to the Reach or Grasp that might bias an increase in RFA expected counts during this epoch.

Model 5: multi-unit spike counts prior to Reach onset (all outcomes). This "control" model is potentially also very interesting. There are statistically significant fixed effects for both Area (p << 0.001; DF = 80179; tStat = -6.24) and the interaction Area*Group (P << 0.001; DF = 80179; tStat = -5.58), which indicate that on average, RFA has a reduction in the expected number of spikes during this epoch that is "removed" from the behavior, but with the partial-dependence plot indicating that this effect may be primarily driven by the interaction term, which sees a substantially lower number of expected spikes in RFA of Ischemia rats (34.79 expected spikes) by comparison to any of the other combinations (41.52 expected spikes in Ischemia*CFA; 40.99 expected spikes in Intact*RFA; and 41.39 expected spikes in Intact*CFA). The contrast between the relatively similar expected spike counts for both areas in the Intact group, compared to the large reduction in expected spikes in the Ischemia group during this epoch suggests that, at least during pre-movement epochs, the Interhemispheric Inhibition hypothesis remains viable. However, in general, during the execution and "read-out" of the motor behavior, the comparative increase of spiking in RFA of Ischemia rats suggests that Inhibition may play less of a roll during the actual behavioral execution itself.

General Comment

Notice that the shape of the output manifold for the recovered generalized linear mixed-effects models changes substantially depending upon what times we select relative to the behavioral alignment event. One reason that it is difficult to study this system purely in terms of unit excitation is because defining critical temporal epochs that are used for such analyses has a tremendous impact on the statistical model end-point. A dynamical systems perspective, in which the cortical areas under control are considered as part of a control system, allows a broader perspective in order to discern qualitative trends.

Organize output into table

G = table(Outcome,Align,tStart,tStop,glme);
G.Outcome = string(G.Outcome);
G.Align = string(G.Align);
G.Properties.VariableUnits = {'','','ms','ms',''};
G.Properties.VariableDescriptions = {'Trial result',...
'Behavioral alignment event','Relative start time',...
'Relative end time','Generalized Linear Mixed-Effects Model'};
G.Properties.UserData = struct('type',"SpikeCountsGLME",'modelspec',mdl);
G.Properties.Description = ...

Check model residuals

In general, the models are not completely accurate and are likely missing some covariates, but they are still pretty good.
One noted point is that we are analyzing multi-unit spiking (not sorted single-unit activity); therefore our assumption of a Poisson process does not entirely hold since it's more likely that counts on each channel are the result of a hyper- or hypo-exponential process, depending on the architecture of nearby detected units. We chose to use multi-unit activity because the density of the electrode arrays used was not high enough for us to make good use of spatial features in combination with temporal features of the waveforms, as might be done with tetrodes or newer high-density arrays such as Neuropixels.
Another likely source of error that our model does not capture is the relative temporal proximity of the behavioral events of interest; the Reach and Grasp are typically only separated by a few-hundred milliseconds, and this temporal "smearing" of activity may also account for the skewness of the residual distributions.

In general, we notice that the residuals are right-skewed (top row panels) and slightly unbalanced when plotting the Fitted Value vs. Residuals (although my intuition is that the apparently linear lower-bound on the residuals vs. fitted values for lower fitted values probably relates to the model dealing with counts that can be "close" to zero, without any formal explanation for why I think that). We do not see an indication of trends being driven by any particular observation with exceedingly high leverage, which is reassuring; the histogram and normal probability plots are not perfect, but I think given the information we are working with, this is a pretty reasonable model fit.
